{"parentUuid":"1f085926-e995-4359-a714-f8f66ddaf6ec","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"795b6292-899f-43d1-822d-8e0cc35d6b7d","agentId":"a4053cef465153bd0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HYa9kDPygHVdqKTQ7qDx5s","type":"tool_result","content":"30\t        \"idempotency_key\": \"idem-1\",\n31\t    }\n32\t    payload.update(overrides)\n33\t    return payload\n34\t\n35\t\n36\tasync def _bulk_insert_rollups(\n37\t    postgres_url, *, api_key_id: int, metric: str, window_start: datetime, count: int\n38\t) -> None:\n39\t    \"\"\"Directly seed `usage_rollup` rows via a single set-based INSERT — the\n40\t    cap/perf tests need tens of thousands of rows, which is impractical to\n41\t    seed one ingest POST at a time.\"\"\"\n42\t    from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import create_async_engine\n43\t\n44\t    engine = create_async_engine(postgres_url)\n45\t    async with engine.begin() as connection:\n46\t        await connection.execute(\n47\t            text(\n48\t                \"\"\"\n49\t                INSERT INTO usage_rollup (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity, event_count)\n50\t                SELECT :api_key_id, 'cust_' || lpad(gs::text, 8, '0'), :metric, :window_start, 1, 1\n51\t                FROM generate_series(1, :count) AS gs\n52\t                \"\"\"\n53\t            ),\n54\t            {\"api_key_id\": api_key_id, \"metric\": metric, \"window_start\": window_start, \"count\": count},\n55\t        )\n56\t    await engine.dispose()\n57\t\n58\t\n59\tasync def test_export_is_header_only_csv_for_empty_result(client, make_api_key):\n60\t    \"\"\"AC12: a caller with no matching rollups gets 200 with a single header\n61\t    line, never 404.\"\"\"\n62\t    presented_key, _ = await make_api_key()\n63\t    response = await client.get(\"/v1/usage/export\", headers={\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {presented_key}\"})\n64\t\n65\t    assert response.status_code == 200\n66\t    assert response.text == \"customer_id,metric,window_start,total_quantity\\r\\n\"\n67\t\n68\t\n69\tasync def test_export_with_no_filters_returns_all_caller_rows(client, make_api_key):"}]},"uuid":"01151865-0355-4bfc-95d7-c2883aba576e","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:49:06.481Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1f085926-e995-4359-a714-f8f66ddaf6ec","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"01151865-0355-4bfc-95d7-c2883aba576e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a4053cef465153bd0","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccs9BsUhXFvKrvy2jcE28","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":124,"cache_creation_input_tokens":999,"cache_read_input_tokens":41385,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":999,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccs9BqzuBdiwSLT3xbCNK","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"eb78b6e0-5751-4ef8-bf37-dd285d5ac90d","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:49:17.793Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"eb78b6e0-5751-4ef8-bf37-dd285d5ac90d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a4053cef465153bd0","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccs9BsUhXFvKrvy2jcE28","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Analysis complete. Here are the cleanup candidates in the usage-export change-set, ranked.\n\n## Candidates\n\n**1. Dead duplicate constant `EXPORT_COLUMNS`** — `src/services/usage_export_service.py:32`\n`EXPORT_COLUMNS = (\"customer_id\", \"metric\", \"window_start\", \"total_quantity\")` is never referenced anywhere (grep-confirmed: only appears here and in plan.md). The module already imports and uses `EXPORT_HEADER` from `src/api/csv_export.py:13` for the one place a column list is needed (`writer.writerow(EXPORT_HEADER)` at line 114). This is a third copy of the same 4-column tuple (also the fields of `UsageRollupExportRecord`).\nCost: a future column rename updates `EXPORT_HEADER` and the record but silently leaves this stale tuple behind, and a reader has to chase a \"constant\" that drives nothing. Delete it.\n\n**2. `_bulk_insert_rollups` copy-pasted across the two new integration test files** — `tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py:47` duplicates `tests/integration/test_usage_export_endpoint.py:36`\nSame signature, same set-based `INSERT ... generate_series` SQL, only the docstring differs. Both are new files in this change-set.\nCost: the seeding SQL (or the `usage_rollup` column set) has to be edited in two places; drift makes the perf and correctness suites seed subtly different data. Hoist one copy into `tests/integration/conftest.py` as a fixture (alongside `make_api_key`) and import it in both.\n\n**3. `_nearest_rank_percentile` re-implemented instead of reused** — `tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py:38`\nByte-for-byte the same helper already living at `tests/integration/test_perf_smoke.py:81` (the new copy's own docstring admits it \"mirror[s] `test_perf_smoke.py`'s convention\"). This is a re-implementation of an existing helper rather than an import.\nCost: two definitions of the same percentile math to keep in lockstep; if the nearest-rank convention is ever corrected in one, the export perf gate quietly uses the old formula. Extract to a shared test util and import.\n\n**4. Window-bound constants duplicated between the two usage schemas** — `src/api/schemas/usage_export.py:16-17`\n`_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKBACK = timedelta(days=90)` and `_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKAHEAD = timedelta(hours=1)`, plus the `earliest/latest` bound computation, are verbatim copies of `src/api/schemas/usage.py:15-16` (the docstring says it reuses \"the same `[now-90d, now+1h]` window-bound idiom `usage.py` uses\" — but it copies the numbers rather than importing them).\nCost: the supported query window is now defined in two files; changing 90d/1h on one endpoint silently leaves the other endpoint accepting a different range. Import the two constants (or a shared `assert_within_supported_window` helper) from `schemas/usage.py`.\n\n**5. The 100k cap re-stated as literal strings in the route's OpenAPI block** — `src/api/routes/usage_export.py:36,42`\n`MAX_EXPORT_ROWS = 100_000` is the source of truth in `usage_export_service.py:31`, but the `_EXPORT_RESPONSES` 422 description and example message hardcode `100000` / `100,000` as literal text.\nCost: raising/lowering the cap updates the enforced value and the runtime 422 message (which is built from `MAX_EXPORT_ROWS`) but leaves the served OpenAPI docs advertising the old number — a doc/DAST-schema drift. Interpolate `MAX_EXPORT_ROWS` (import it) into the response metadata.\n\n**6. `_require_authenticated_and_throttled` re-declared per route (weaker — likely intentional)** — `src/api/routes/usage_export.py:52-59`\nIdentical to the same-named dependency in `src/api/routes/usage.py:16-23`. Both docstrings explicitly say it is \"kept as a sibling, not a shared import, per the existing per-route convention,\" and `events.py` follows the same pattern, so this is a deliberate, established convention rather than accidental duplication.\nCost: low/arguable — if the auth→throttle ordering ever needs to change it must change in every route, but the convention is intentional and consistent. Flagging only for completeness; I would not act on this one.\n\nNotes: The route/service two-module split and the shared `_export_filter_clause_and_params` helper in `usage_repo.py:74` are genuinely good reuse (count and stream queries can't drift). I found no export-specific env-var/param YAGNI knobs (the `max_connections=300` and k6/uvicorn commentary lives in the pre-existing, unmodified `integration/conftest.py`, out of this change-set). Strongest, highest-confidence fixes are #1, #2, and #3."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":124,"cache_creation_input_tokens":999,"cache_read_input_tokens":41385,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":999,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccs9BqzuBdiwSLT3xbCNK","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"f06983dc-adfc-47bd-94d5-0b24cfa89d80","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:49:40.194Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
